  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>Which is least soluble?</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "Na$$_2$$S"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "MgS"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "MgCl$$_2$$"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "NaCl"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "B"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>More the covalent nature of compounds lesser will be its solubility.</p>\n<p>Also, according to Fajan's rule, lesser be the size of cation or more be size of anion, species show more covalent nature.</p>\n<p>As, $$\\mathrm{Mg}$$ show +2 oxidation state and $$\\mathrm{Na}$$ is in +1 oxidation state the size of $$\\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}$$ is less than that of $$\\mathrm{Na}^{+}$$. On the other hand, sulphur is in $$-2$$ oxidation state while chlorine is in $$-1$$ oxidation state, therefore sulphur anion is larger in size. Thus, among the given species, the combination of $$\\mathrm{Mg}$$ and sulphur ($$\\mathrm{S}$$) show maximum covalent nature and therefore is least soluble.</p>\n<p>Hence, option (b) is the correct.</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2019,
    "yearKey": "aiims-2019",
    "difficulty": null
  },
